<font color="#FF0000">TO COOK BARELA</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug 13 21:08:44 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
Speaking as one individual, I can assure you that I never was ashamed to have served in Vietnam. I answered the call.<br><br>
Not only did I serve my country when requested, I accomplished many things. There is no way in the world ANYONE could ever deny these (my) accomplishments! If the so called, &quot;COWARDS&quot;, you have the inclination to berate in each of your posts could take away that which you accomplished then your accomplishments wouldn't be worth much, would they?<br><br>
To be sure, vets were blamed for events in Vietnam. That is not the case TODAY.<br><br>
None died in vain. For to visit The Wall, is to come to the realization that inscribed are 58,000 reasons why this country should never become involved in another ill defined war. If blaming someone is so vital to you, then blame those who got us involved in Vietnam.<br><br>
Your last paragraph says much. You talk of moving forward, yet you wish to &quot;expose&quot; those didn't serve. How can you look forward while harboring a vendetta against those who protested a war 30 years ago? <br><br>
It is good that we go to annual reunions. I fail to see the point in allowing bitterness to detract from these memorable and meaningful events.<br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


